{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478189"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:11:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:11:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17006"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17006"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.8,0.04,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9696"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68208"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9696"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17006"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53665"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"},{"type":"tags","id":"1040"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"6488"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22827"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37099"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68208"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-month-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of fever, irritability and poor feeding. She has had two previous urinary tract infections in the past six months and was diagnosed with vesicoureteral reflux following investigation. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her growth and development are normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 140/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 35/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. Urinalysis shows leucocytes 3+, nitrites positive, and blood 1+. Urine microscopy reveals \u0026gt;100 \u00d7 10\u2076/L white blood cells. A renal ultrasound is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely ultrasound finding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal renal architecture","Hydronephrosis","Renal calculi","Renal cyst","Renal mass"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant presents with features of a urinary tract infection (UTI) and has a concerning history of recurrent UTIs, with known vesicoureteral reflux (VUR). In children with VUR, urine flows backwards from the bladder into the ureters and sometimes into the kidneys, leading to characteristic ultrasound findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydronephrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely finding on ultrasound in this case. It appears as dilation of the renal collecting system, including the renal pelvis and calyces. The severity of hydronephrosis often correlates with the grade of VUR, with higher grades showing more significant dilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal renal architecture\u003C/strong\u003E would be unexpected given the known diagnosis of VUR. While mild VUR may occasionally show normal anatomy, the recurrent nature of infections suggests a more significant anatomical abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal calculi\u003C/strong\u003E are uncommon in infants and would be unlikely to cause recurrent UTIs. They typically cause sudden onset of severe pain rather than recurrent infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is an unlikely finding in this clinical scenario. Simple renal cysts are rare in infants and do not typically cause recurrent UTIs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal mass\u003C/strong\u003E would not explain the pattern of recurrent UTIs. While masses can occasionally cause obstruction leading to infection, they would typically present with other symptoms such as a palpable mass or haematuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter identifying hydronephrosis on ultrasound, the next appropriate step would be to perform a voiding cystourethrogram (VCUG) to grade the VUR if not already done. This information is crucial for determining appropriate management, which may include prophylactic antibiotics or surgical intervention depending on the severity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydronephrosis is a common finding in children with vesicoureteral reflux.","Renal ultrasound findings in vesicoureteral reflux include dilated renal pelvis, calyces, and ureters.","The severity of hydronephrosis correlates with the grade of vesicoureteral reflux."],"references":["Lotfollahzadeh S, Leslie SW, Aeddula NR. Vesicoureteral Reflux. [Updated 2024 Apr 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563262/","Cajigas-Loyola SC, Chow JS, Hayatghaibi S, Iyer RS, Kwon J, Rubesova E, S\u00e1nchez-Jacob R, Wyers M, Otero HJ. Imaging of Vesicoureteral Reflux: AJR Expert Panel Narrative Review. AJR Am J Roentgenol. 2024 Jun;222(6):e2329741"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53665"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17006"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53665"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T14:48:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T14:49:44+10:30"},"relatio